description: Originally serialized in Kadokawa's Marukatsu Famicon, the 5-volume MADARA represents the first collaboration between artist Tajima and writer Otsuka. Tajima recently garnered notoriety for his character design work on the animated segments of Quentin Tarantino's Kill Bill Vol. 1. MADARA tells the story of an apprentice blacksmith in a rural village who gets by using artificial limbs created by his adoptive father. But when a chance encounter with the demon Moki reveals Madara's true destiny, he's catapulted into a mythic quest! His real father, the evil despot Miroku, feared long ago that Madara was destined to kill him and rule in his place. After Madara was born with tremendous powers, his body was cut up, and the parts divided amongst eight evil generals. Now Madara, with the help of a band of freedom fighters and a magical sword, sets out to retrieve his body parts and defeat his brothers, who covet the throne. As he fights his way across the world, he contemplates the prophecy: How will he wrest control of the kingdom from his father and win the people their freedom?

Madara and Kaos are similar creatures. Born with extraordinary powers, both had them taken away by Emperor Miroku. A legend foretold that the warrior destined to dethrone Miroku would have the crest of a dragon etched on his forehead. Madara bears this crest. In order to prevent the ancient prophecy from becoming a reality, Miroku separated his son's body into eight partsdividing them amongst his demon Moki generals for safekeeping. Kaos, too, has suffered a lossthe entire left half of his body is being held captive by Miroku. In order to survive the Mokiridden world, both warriors have artificial limbs and gadgets to compensate for their missing body parts.

There is one difference between these two adversaries: destiny versus desire. Even though Madara fits the profile of the young warrior destined to overthrow the evil dictator and become the true king of all beings, Kaos covets the throne and has far superior warrior training. Although Kaos has "pledged" allegiance to Miroku and been ordered to kill Madara, Kaos plans to follow through solely to eliminate his rival.

And now, as fate would have it, these two combatants prepare to faceoff in the Corridor of Fire. Will destiny prevail? Or will desire? It's Madara versus Kaos in Volume 2 of MADARA!

Months have passed since Madara vanished. Kaos and Kirin returned to the river village. They have joined forces with Loki and his people, who are now attacking the remainder Emperor Miroku's forces in a formal rebellion. Jofuku assists the people by preparing special weapons; the battles are going well. But Miroku and his demons are easily beaten.Word begins to spread about an immensely powerful warrior with a magical sword that can slay demons with a single stroke. The description is similar to Madaracan he have reappeared? Kirin and Kaos return to the Corridor of Fire to find the answers.

Loki and Jamira follow Seishinja to the peaceful village of Risan, far from the war. They find Madara living as a peaceful villager and entreat him to return to the battle to defeat his own father, Emperor Miroku, but he refuses. Then, old man Sukne reveals the presence of another Kusanagi sword, the Maken Kusanagi, and claims that if the two swords are combined, their power could determine the outcome of the war. Now that the Emperor and his army know about the two swords, they determine to kill the two rebels and take the weapons. But Madara must face someone with matching powers who proves to be his greatest opponenthis own brother, Kageo. Kageo tries to kill Madara and capture both the Shinken Kusanagi and the Maken Kusanagi. With Madara dead and the two swords of power in the hands of the enemy, things look bleak indeed.

Don't miss the thrilling series finale! Madara has joined forces with Seishinja and Kaos to challenge Kageo and the remaining Moki army. Will they have enough strength to crush this threat? Even if they prevail, will they have the power to confront and defeat Miroku, the demon emperor? Or will eternal darkness be cast upon the land?

Moebius, the internationally acclaimed illustrator of countless graphic novels and film designer for Alien, Blade Runner and The Fifth Element influenced a generation when he joined forces with writer Alexandro Jodorowsky for THE INCAL! This new volume, a perfect jumping on point, presents the first part of the classic adventure of science-fiction detective John Difool, illustrated by Moebius and written by Jodorowsky and updated with new colors by Beltran. John Difool, a low class detective in a degenerate world, finds his life turned upside down when he discovers an ancient artifact called "The Incal." Difool's adventures will bring him into conflict with the galaxy's greatest warrior, The Metabaron, and will pit him against the awesome powers of the Technopope. These encounters and many more make up a tale of comical and cosmic proportions that has Difool fighting for not only his very survival, but also the survival of the entire universe.

Final volume. Takatoh has agreed to help Yuzu take care of Shou, even though it means putting his own dreams on hold. But Yuzu knows that's not something her sister would have wanted and insists that he follows his original plans, even if it means leaving Japan. Meanwhile, Yuzu has some choices to make about her own future. Will she sacrifice her dreams for Shou?
name: Volume Two
